descript.abstract: This is a "hot spot" data set representing biological diversity, created by aggregation of predictive habitat maps for wading birds, important natural communities, and 44 focal species. It also includes known species and community locations.
descript.purpose: This data is intended to aid conservation and planning efforts in the state of Florida.

idinfo.useconst:
THE DATA INCLUDED IN THIS APPLICATION ARE BASED ON INTERPRETATION OF AVAILABLE INFORMATION AND SHOULD NOT BE CONSTRUED AS LEGALLY BINDING.
Scale is an important factor in data usage. Certain scale data sets are not suitable for some projects, analysis, or modeling purposes. Please be sure you are using the best available data.
1:24000 scale data sets are recommended for projects that are at the county level. 1:24000 data should NOT be used for high accuracy base mapping such as property parcel boundaries.
1:100000 scale data sets are recommended for projects that are at the multi-county or regional level. 1:250000 scale data sets are recommended for projects that are at the regional or state level or larger.

attracc.attraccr: Data was created from Landsat Thematic Mapper Satellite Imagery dated 1985-1989 (30m pixels) in order to classify 22 land cover types (i.e., wildlife habitats) known in the state of Florida. The FFWCC worked with a team of ecologists to reconstruct Floridian habitat types.

dataqual.complete: In 1994, the FLORIDA FISH & WILDLIFE CONSERVATION COMMISSION (FFWCC) published Closing the Gaps in Florida's Wildlife Habitat Conservation System, which implemented the use of Land Sat images to reconstruct Florida's habitat types. This data layer was reviewed and used in a number of planning initiatives.

srcinfo.srccontr: Represent areas with a high degree of overlap for 54 declining species of wildlife plus known occurrences of flora, fauna, & natural communities.

procstep.procdesc:
The process step describes, in general, the process used in the production of data sets. The originating agencies created the original coverage. GeoPlan, during the QA/QC process included the following aspects: (1) Adding the DESCRIPT item, based on Value Item Description (2) Reprojecting the coverage to FGDL Albers (3) Checking precision, tolerances and other factors which affect spatial data. In addition, this data layer contains information from the following report: Cox, J., Kautz, R., Maclaughlin, M., and T. Gilbert. 1994. Closing the Gaps in Florida's Wildlife Habitat Conservation System. Office of Environmental Services, Florida Game and Freshwater Fish Commission.
